When LDAP Delegated Authentication is used it can be configured to support user object filter only via direct manipulation of database table. To be more specific this is 'cwd_directory_attribute' table and mapulated attributes are "ldap.user.filter" and "ldap.user.objectclass". In my case I'm using ldap.user.filter="(memberOf=cn=jira,ou=groups,dc=mycompany,dc=com)" and ldap.user.objectclass="inetOrgPerson". It works perfectly. I had a hope that underlying implementation is the same as LDAP Directory. Obviously it is, at least is seems like that. My point is that this functionality already exists and there is no reason to don't use it again for LDAP Delegated Authentication.

For me personaly this is quite useful, because I can emulate disabled jira account.

# Configure the OpenLDAP directory.
# Notice that the user object filter is: {{(objectclass=inetorgperson)}}
# Edit the directory you just created and change its type to {{OpenLDAP (Read-Only Posix Schema}}
# (*DEFECT*) Notice that none of the "advanced settings" the user object is still {{(objectclass=inetorgperson)}}

It is misleading to allow this dropdown to change if it actually does nothing. We can:

# Don't allow the "Directory Type" to be changed (i.e. make read-only text). If we cant change the values then why imply that we can?
# Make the UI more advanced. A change it the type needs to somehow fill in the form. I have no idea how you deal with changes an admin may have made. 
# Something cooler.

